Review: Incredibly impactful work, blending the concepts and research of the book it’s based on with the life of the author, leading to a format closer to a long form video essay than a straightforward narrative. I’m not sure if that structure totally works here, and maybe a documentary is more suited for how it wants to convey its information, but as it stands it’s a flawed yet fascinating work. Aunjanue Ellis-Taylor and Niecy Nash-Betts are great.
Schlocky low-budget B-movie horror comedy done right
There’s an argument to be made that this isn’t even a real movie and we all just simultaneously dreamed it up

It’s missing the purposeful low-budget aesthetic of Black Dynamite, so it just looks cheap. It also far too long. Even so, as it stands it’s alright. It’s funny in fits and starts and has some great parody jokes in there. It just needed to embrace the low budget works it’s parodying, all of which were much shorter than this one.
As charming as Cuoco and Oyelowo can be, this is too dull and lifeless to even attempt to put energy into any fully formed review

This movie is so incredibly dumb. The level of galaxy brain needed by the screenwriter to escalate the plot the way it’s done here would be admirable if it didn’t make me concerned for his well-being. Incredible movie.
Not sure if the ending lands as well as it could’ve, but it’s a fun ride nonetheless
Despite being somewhat tonally uneven and somewhat episodic storytelling, this is another striking feature from Jeymes Samuels. More thoughts to come.

Sporadically funny, but more of a satire that makes you think “that’s kind of funny” than actually makes you laugh. The story is pretty muddled and drags a good deal in the middle, but the first and third act are weird and bizarre enough to keep you engaged. That, and of course the stunning black & white cinematography.
It looks great, has a solid style and good action sequences. What more could you want?
Another just-okay movie with great performances
